DETROIT ASU sprint star
Henry Carr and his high school
sweetheart we're married in their
hometown Sunday.


Carr, 81, holder of the 20.3
seconds world record for the
22O-yard dash, and Glenda F.
Nixon, 20, Michigan State Uni
versity coed, we're married at
Hartford Avenue Baptist Church.


The newly weds returned to
Tempe, where Carr, a junior at
Arizona State, will resume his
studies. Glenda said she will
skip the current semester at
Michigan State.

The body of a 25-year-old
Phoenix woman was found last
week in a blood-spattered room
in the home of Carl Watson
27, oO3 E. Southern Pacific DR..


Police identified the woman as
Mrs. Theresa Simmons. Of l445
E. Madison. They said suicide
note was found and a gas oven
was turned on.


However, an Arizona Public
Service Co., investigator said
there was not enough natural
gas in the room to cause death.
Detective Jack Cozad said the
body showed no external injuries.
Officers are seeking Watson for
Questioning.

ager in the Foods Division of
Lever Brothers Company, an
nounced Ernest l.. Whitney, Jr.,
marketing vice president of the
division. The Foods Division
markets the company's marga-
rines, shortening, dessert top
pings and pancake syrup.


He had been a promotion ma
terials specialist since joining
the company in 1861. He pre-
viously had been associated with
the F & M Schaefer Brewing
Company and Schenley Distillers
Company.


A graduate of the University
of Chicago with a BIS. degree
in sociology, Mr.. Gregory was
a flight officer with the US.
Air Corps during World War
II. He resides in New York City
with his wife and two children.

FARMVILLE, VA. The man
who organized free schools In
Prince Edward County from
scratch after the public schools
had been closed for four years
said he hoped the job would
not have to be done again next
fall.


DR.. Neil ]. Sullivan, superin-
tendent of the Prince Edward
Free School Ass ociation, warned
county officials to begin taking
steps now to reopen the public
schools in the fall.


He said officials from other
school districts we're making al
most daily visits to Farmville
to sign up teachers due to leave
when the one-year free school
ends in August.


Arguments which could lead
to an order to reopen the public
schools will be heard by the US.
Supreme Court in Washington
Tuesday.


Prince Edward closed its pub
lie schools in 1859 to avoid court
ordered classroom integration.
The free schools we're organized
at the insistence of President
Kennedy, and are attended mainly
by Negro students.

arrested the II year old mother
of Massachusetts Gov. Endico OFT
Peabody Monday and used dogs
to Jail Negro youths as racial
demonstrations reached new
peak.


Mrs. Malcolm Peabody was
arrested by Police 1t. E. ].
Irwin as she sat with five St.
Augustine Negro women in the

dining room of the Ponce de
Leon Motor Lodge.


With typical New England re-
serve, Mrs. Peabody smiled and
said calmly, when Irwin asked
her if she was going to leave:


''We are not going to leave"


Told that she was under ar
rest, she rose quietly and walked
with the others ahead of a group
of officers to waiting car.

Mrs. Thomas maple Ley
Pratt, l7l6 W. Mohave, heads the
state delegation to the western
regional convention of Alpha Chi
Pi Omega Sorority and Frater-
nifty.


The meetings will be held at
the Hilton Hotel in Denver, April
So.


Mrs. Pratt, local chapter ba-
sileus will be accompanied by
Mesdames Delois Moore, Alma
Berkeley, Beatrice White, Chris
tine Jackson Tapp. Maefaire
Alexander, Velma MCGEE, Idella
Soublet, Emma Johnson and Mar
celine Murray.


She Is serving her second con-
secutive term as basileus. Her
other activities include member
of Board of directors of the Ur-
ban League. grand district deputy
of IBPOEW, NAACP, PISA trus-
tee and First Institutional Baptist
Church.


Mrs. Pratt owns and manages
the Lady Ebonee Beauty Center.


She will head the committee
which will return Ebonys Fash
ion Fair to the city later this
year.
